x4freetext: The experiments were carried out at
the National Superconducting Cyclotron Laboratory
(NSCL).
The Coupled Cyclotron Facility (CCF) provided a fully
stripped 48Ca20+ primary beam for the experiment at
102 MeV/nucleon.
The exotic beam experiments were also performed at
the NSCL. In these experiments, a 140 MeV/nucleon
48Ca beam provided by the CCF was fragmented on a
beryllium target with a thickness of 650 mg/cm2.
The resulting heavy-ion fragments were filtered
with the A1900 fragment separator into two separate
cocktail beams with energies of about
100 MeV/nucleon. The first cocktail beam contained
mostly 40S with some 42Cl contamination and the
second contained mostly 42S and 44Cl.
48Ca beam: 100 % pure
40S beam: 84.5 % pure with main contaminant 42Cl
42S beam: 57.6 % pure with main contaminant 44Cl
A liquid deuterium target was used instead of a CD2
target because it provided a pure deuterium target
without background from the reactions of the beams
with carbon. The target consisted of a cylindrical
cell 30 mm in diameter by 9 mm long. The liquid
deuterium was contained by two thin aluminum windows
that were each 0.2 mm thick. The target was filled
with liquid deuterium to a pressure of 1100 hPa
(1100 mbar), producing a target 11.2 mm thick.
Assuming the density of liquid deuterium is 0.169
g/cm3, then the areal density of the target was
The beam was transported to the target position
of the S800 spectrograph where it bombarded the RIKEN
liquid deuterium target
The flux of the 48Ca beam on the target was monitored
during the experiment by a transmission plastic
scintillator at the entrance of the S800.
The reaction products were cleanly separated in
the data using a combination of software gates for
the ion chamber, TOF, and position in the focal plane
In the cases where complete momentum distributions
were detected in the focal plane, the main
uncertainties arise from the choice of software gates
used for the particle identification (10%), the
stability of the beam current (5%), and the pressure
drifts in the target cell discussed earlier (1%).
These systematic errors are independent and are added
in quadrature, giving a total uncertainty of 11%.
